select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ระบบ EMS / quality / business of medicine: medical malpractice + surgical complications

คำถาม: how to handle adverse outcome + communication', '[{"label":"A","text":"Avoid all communication"},{"label":"B","text":"**Adverse event management + communication — open disclosure + patient safety**: (1) **Immediate response**: - Address ongoing medical care first (treat patient, stabilize, escalate) - Document accurately + factually; (2) **Open disclosure / ''Sorry Works''**: - Communicate transparently with patient + family - Express empathy + concern (apology for distress experienced, not necessarily admission of fault) - Explain what happened in understandable language - Discuss what investigation will be undertaken - Discuss plan for ongoing care + how to prevent recurrence - Avoid speculation + blame; - Evidence: open disclosure REDUCES litigation + improves trust (Michigan Open Disclosure, COPIC, Kaiser studies); (3) **Apology laws / ''I''m sorry'' laws** — many jurisdictions (~ 39 US states, multiple international) protect expressions of empathy from being used as admission of liability; check local; (4) **Root Cause Analysis (RCA)** — systematic event analysis: - Multidisciplinary team - Timeline reconstruction - Identify contributing factors (people, process, equipment, environment, communication) - ''Just culture'' — system vs individual - Develop action plan - Implement + monitor; (5) **M&M Conferences** — surgical tradition: - Case-based learning - Educational + safety improvement - Confidential (peer review protection) + non-punitive in best practice; (6) **Quality improvement processes**: - Failure Mode + Effects Analysis (FMEA) — proactive risk assessment - PDSA cycles (Plan-Do-Study-Act) - Lean / Six Sigma methodology; (7) **Documentation principles**: - Contemporaneous + factual - Avoid speculation, blame, emotion - Late entries marked + dated - Original records preserved; (8) **Legal considerations** when adverse event: - Notify risk management / hospital administration - Consult legal counsel - Maintain communication with patient (open disclosure within legal framework) - Quality of care matters AND communication matters — both reduce litigation - ''Disclose + offer'' programs (e.g., University of Michigan) — proactive disclosure + apology + compensation — reduces overall claims + costs; (9) **Patient safety culture**: - Just culture - Blameless reporting (incident reports, near-miss reporting) - Leadership commitment - Continuous learning; (10) **Personal impact**: - Second victim phenomenon — physician/team also affected by adverse outcome - Peer support, mental health support, debriefing - Burnout prevention"},{"label":"C","text":"Blame individual staff"},{"label":"D","text":"Hide information"},{"label":"E","text":"Refuse to discuss with patient"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Adverse event management + open disclosure** — central to modern patient safety + culture. **Open disclosure** (Australia, UK, US trends — Joint Commission, AHA, ACOG advocate): 1. **Acknowledge** the event happened 2. **Empathize** + offer sincere apology for impact 3. **Explain** in understandable terms what happened (factually, without speculation) 4. **Discuss** investigation + steps to prevent recurrence 5. **Continue** care + communication 6. **Compensation** if appropriate **Evidence**: open disclosure programs (Michigan, COPIC, Kaiser, VA): - Decreased litigation + costs - Improved patient satisfaction - Improved staff morale - Improved safety culture **Apology laws**: ~ 39 US states + many international jurisdictions protect expressions of empathy/sympathy from being used as admission of liability. Allows physicians to apologize without legal jeopardy. **Root Cause Analysis (RCA)** principles: - System focus, not individual blame - Identify contributing factors (5 Whys, Ishikawa fishbone) - Generate corrective actions - Implement + monitor - ''Just culture'' — distinguish system error vs individual reckless behavior vs honest mistake **''Just culture''** (Marx, Reason): - Three behaviors: human error (console), at-risk (coach), reckless (sanction) - Encourages reporting + learning - Removes fear of blame for honest mistake **Failure Mode + Effects Analysis (FMEA)** — proactive: anticipate failure modes before they occur; mitigate risk. **PDSA cycle** (Plan-Do-Study-Act) — quality improvement framework. **M&M Conference** — surgical learning tradition; case-based; peer review protection; educational not punitive in optimal practice. **Documentation** in adverse events: factual + contemporaneous + non-judgmental; avoid speculation, opinion, blame; legal protection by clear documentation. **Second victim phenomenon** — clinician/team distress after adverse event affecting patient: physical, psychological, professional impact; peer support, debriefing, mental health resources critical; programs like RISE (Resilience in Stressful Events) at Johns Hopkins. **Disclose + Offer Programs** (University of Michigan, others) — proactive disclosure of error + apology + compensation offer — reduces overall claims, costs, and patient harm.', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'ems_mgmt', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'Joint Commission Sentinel Event Reporting; AHRQ Open Disclosure; ACOG Committee Opinion; Boothman RC et al. (Michigan Open Disclosure)', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_ems_mgmt'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
      and q.board_specialty = 'surgery'
      and q.scenario = 'ระบบ EMS / quality / business of medicine: medical malpractice + surgical complications

คำถาม: how to handle adverse outcome + communication'
  );

