select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: trauma evaluation — primary + secondary survey

คำถาม: ATLS principles + trauma evaluation', '[{"label":"A","text":"No systematic approach needed"},{"label":"B","text":"**ATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) — systematic approach**: (1) **Pre-arrival**: communication with EMS, team activation, prepare equipment, blood products, OR notification; (2) **Primary survey ABCDE — identify + treat life-threats simultaneously**: - **A — Airway** with cervical spine protection: assess patency, talking = patent; obstructed → jaw thrust, suction, oral/nasal airway, supraglottic, intubation (rapid sequence with C-spine inline immobilization), surgical airway last resort; - **B — Breathing**: inspect, palpate, percuss, auscultate; identify life-threats: tension pneumothorax (needle/finger decompression — 5th ICS anterior axillary), open pneumothorax (3-sided occlusive dressing), massive hemothorax (chest tube > 1.5L initial OR > 200 mL/hr × 4h → OR), flail chest (positive pressure ventilation if respiratory failure); - **C — Circulation** + hemorrhage control: assess pulse, capillary refill, mental status, BP; identify hemorrhage sources: external (direct pressure, tourniquet, hemostatic gauze), thoracic (chest tube), abdominal (FAST), pelvic (binder + angio + REBOA), retroperitoneal, long bone fractures (splinting + ortho); 2 large-bore IV (16-18g) or IO; type & cross; balanced resuscitation (1:1:1 PRC:FFP:Plt early in massive bleed per PROPPR); permissive hypotension (no TBI); TXA early (CRASH-2 + CRASH-3); MTP activation; calcium (citrate binding) - **D — Disability**: GCS (E4V5M6 = 15), pupil (size + reactivity), gross motor; head trauma signs - **E — Exposure + environmental**: completely undress, log roll, look for occult injuries (back, axilla, perineum); rewarm aggressively (hypothermia worsens coagulopathy + acidosis = lethal triad); avoid cold IV fluid; (3) **Adjuncts to primary survey**: FAST exam (or eFAST including lung), CXR, pelvis XR, ECG, ABG, lactate, type + cross, urinary catheter (if no urethral injury — blood at meatus, high-riding prostate), NG/OG; (4) **Reassess + identify undiagnosed life threats**; (5) **Secondary survey** — head-to-toe systematic exam + AMPLE history (Allergies, Medications, Past, Last meal, Events); only after primary stabilized; identify all injuries — log roll + back exam, head + maxillofacial, neck + C-spine, chest, abdomen + pelvis, perineum + rectal, musculoskeletal, neurological detailed; (6) **Definitive care + transfer** — to appropriate trauma center if needed; do NOT delay definitive care for prolonged workup; OR + IR + ICU coordination; (7) **Tertiary survey** — within 24h, identifies missed injuries (5-10% miss rate without tertiary); (8) **Special populations**: - **Pediatric**: weight-based dosing, anatomical differences, vital sign norms differ, NAT consideration - **Geriatric**: under-triage common due to compensated initial vitals; lower threshold for trauma center - **Pregnant**: maternal first (best for fetus); left lateral tilt (avoid IVC compression > 20 weeks); fetal monitoring; Rh status (Rhogam) - **Anticoagulated**: reversal (PCC, TXA, FFP); reverse first then evaluate; (9) **Damage control resuscitation (DCR) + damage control surgery (DCS)** principles when severely injured; (10) **Communication + handoff** structured (SBAR); patient + family disclosure"},{"label":"C","text":"Random workup"},{"label":"D","text":"Discharge all trauma"},{"label":"E","text":"Single specialty only"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**ATLS** — global standard for trauma initial evaluation + management. Systematic ABCDE primary survey identifies + treats life threats simultaneously; secondary survey for complete injury identification; tertiary survey within 24h for missed injuries (5-10% miss rate). **Primary survey life-threats**: - **Airway**: obstruction → maneuvers → airway adjuncts → intubation → surgical airway - **Breathing**: tension pneumothorax (decompress), open pneumothorax (3-sided dressing + chest tube), massive hemothorax (chest tube; > 1500 mL or > 200 mL/h × 4h → OR), flail chest (PPV if respiratory failure), cardiac tamponade (pericardiocentesis + thoracotomy) - **Circulation**: external bleeding control (pressure, tourniquet, hemostatic), source identification (FAST, CXR, pelvis), IV access (2 large bore), balanced resuscitation, TXA, MTP, calcium - **Disability**: GCS, pupils, gross motor - **Exposure**: undress, log roll, rewarm **Adjuncts**: FAST/eFAST, CXR, pelvis, ECG, ABG, lactate, type + cross, Foley (if no urethral injury), NG. **Pelvic binder** for unstable pelvic fracture before any imaging — temporizes hemorrhage. **REBOA** (Resuscitative Endovascular Balloon Occlusion of Aorta) — emerging adjunct for non-compressible torso hemorrhage in extremis — Zone 1 (above diaphragm) or Zone 3 (below renal); bridge to definitive control. **Damage control resuscitation (DCR)**: balanced products 1:1:1 (PROPPR), permissive hypotension (no TBI), TXA early (CRASH-2 NEJM 2010 within 3h; CRASH-3 NEJM 2019 within 3h of mild-moderate TBI), avoid lethal triad (coagulopathy + hypothermia + acidosis), calcium replacement. **Damage control surgery (DCS)**: abbreviated initial operation — control hemorrhage + contamination, temporary closure → ICU resuscitation → definitive 24-48h. **Trauma center matters**: outcomes 20-25% better in dedicated trauma centers (MacKenzie NEJM 2006). **Special populations**: pediatric (weight-based, family centered), geriatric (under-triage risk, anticoagulation, lower threshold to trauma center, modified Frailty Index), pregnant (resuscitate mom first, left lateral tilt, Rh status), anticoagulated (reverse early).', NULL,
  'easy', 'trauma', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'trauma', 'adult',
  'ATLS 10th Edition; ACS Committee on Trauma Resources for Optimal Care', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
