select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: cancer screening + prevention

คำถาม: evidence-based cancer screening principles', '[{"label":"A","text":"No screening needed"},{"label":"B","text":"**Cancer screening — evidence-based principles**: (1) **General principles of screening (WHO Wilson + Jungner criteria)**: - Disease has high prevalence + significant morbidity/mortality - Recognizable preclinical phase - Effective treatment if found early - Acceptable screening test (sensitivity + specificity + safety + cost) - Adequate facilities for follow-up - Cost-effectiveness; (2) **USPSTF + national guidelines** for major cancers: a. **Colorectal**: - **Average risk**: start age 45 (lowered from 50 per 2021 USPSTF); options: - Colonoscopy q10 yr (gold standard — both detect + remove polyps) - FIT (fecal immunochemical test) annually - FIT-DNA (Cologuard) q3 yr - Sigmoidoscopy q5 yr ± FIT q3 yr - CT colonography q5 yr - **High risk** (family history, IBD, polyposis syndrome): earlier + more frequent b. **Breast**: - **USPSTF 2024**: biennial mammogram age 40-74 (recently lowered from 50) - **ACS**: annual 45-54, then q1-2 yr 55+ - **High risk**: earlier + MRI - **Self-exam** debated (no proven mortality benefit but body awareness) c. **Cervical**: - Pap every 3 yr ages 21-29 - Pap + HPV co-test q5 yr OR Pap q3 yr OR HPV alone q5 yr ages 30-65 - Stop > 65 if adequate prior negative + no high-risk - HPV vaccination prevents most cervical Ca + others (anal, oropharyngeal) — vaccinate age 9-12 d. **Lung**: - **USPSTF 2021**: annual low-dose CT for ages 50-80 + 20 pack-year smoking history + currently smoking or quit < 15 yr ago - Significant mortality reduction (NLST, NELSON trials) e. **Prostate**: - PSA-based screening — controversial - **USPSTF 2018**: shared decision-making age 55-69; individualized; avoid > 70 - Mortality benefit modest; overdiagnosis + overtreatment significant - Black men + family history — start earlier + lower threshold f. **Skin**: visual exam selectively (high-risk: family history, prior, immunosuppressed) g. **HCC** in cirrhosis: US ± AFP q6 mo h. **Pancreatic**: only in high-risk (family history, hereditary syndromes); EUS + MRI/MRCP — investigational i. **Ovarian**: no general screening (TVUS + CA-125 not effective in average risk); BRCA+ — risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy considered; (3) **Risk-based modifications**: - Family history - Genetic syndrome (Lynch — q1-2 yr colonoscopy from 20-25, etc.) - Personal history of cancer - Immunosuppression (transplant — q6-12 mo derm, more frequent other) - Exposure (asbestos, radiation, chemicals); (4) **Limitations + harms of screening**: - Overdiagnosis (detection of cancers that would not have caused harm) - Overtreatment - False positives → workup harm, anxiety, costs - False negatives → false reassurance - Cost; (5) **Shared decision-making** — especially for PSA + mammography at age extremes + benefit-harm equipoise; (6) **Active surveillance** for low-risk indolent cancers (prostate Gleason 6, micropapillary thyroid Ca, low-risk DCIS — emerging) — avoid overtreatment; (7) **Liquid biopsy** for early detection — emerging (Galleri MCED — multi-cancer early detection; PATHFINDER study; not standard yet)"},{"label":"C","text":"Screen everyone for everything"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid all screening"},{"label":"E","text":"Skip risk assessment"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Cancer screening** — selective application of tests to detect cancer or precursors in asymptomatic at-risk individuals. Must meet **WHO Wilson + Jungner criteria** for valid screening. **Mortality-reducing evidence** (RCTs + meta-analyses): - Colorectal: colonoscopy + FIT — substantial mortality reduction - Breast: mammography — modest mortality reduction (more in 50+ than 40s) - Cervical: Pap + HPV — dramatic reduction; HPV vaccination prevents - Lung: low-dose CT in heavy smokers — NLST 20% reduction; NELSON 24% - HCC in cirrhosis: US + AFP — modest benefit; recommended in at-risk **Controversial / debated**: - Prostate (PSA): mortality benefit modest; overdiagnosis substantial; shared decision-making essential - Skin: visual exam — selectively high-risk - Ovarian: no general screening (PLCO trial — no benefit) - Pancreatic: only high-risk (hereditary, syndromes) **Risk stratification** — modifies screening intensity: - Family history - Genetic syndromes (BRCA, Lynch, FAP, MEN, others) - Prior cancer - Exposures (radiation, asbestos, smoking) - Comorbidities (immunosuppression, IBD) - Lifestyle **Screening-related harms**: 1. Overdiagnosis — finding cancers that wouldn''t cause harm in patient''s lifetime (some breast DCIS, some thyroid microcarcinoma, some prostate Gleason 6); leads to overtreatment 2. False positives — additional workup, biopsy harm, anxiety, costs 3. False negatives — false reassurance, delayed diagnosis 4. Radiation (low-dose CT screening) — cumulative 5. Patient burden + cost **Active surveillance** — emerging paradigm for low-risk indolent cancers: - Prostate Gleason 6 — vast majority safe with surveillance vs immediate treatment (ProtecT trial — active monitoring non-inferior to surgery/RT at 10 years for low-risk) - Micropapillary PTC ≤ 1 cm — Japanese protocols (Miyauchi, Ito) - DCIS low-risk — LORIS/LORD trials investigating - Renal small mass — selected **HPV vaccination**: prevents > 90% cervical Ca + substantial anal, vulvar, vaginal, oropharyngeal Ca; routine ages 9-12 (catch-up to 26+); now WHO-recommended global strategy to eliminate cervical cancer. **Multi-cancer Early Detection (MCED)** — emerging liquid biopsy (cfDNA methylation): Galleri (PATHFINDER, NHS-Galleri trials); not standard yet; questions about lead-time bias + downstream cascade; promising but evolving.', NULL,
  'medium', 'hemato_onco', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'hemato_onco', 'adult',
  'USPSTF; ACS; NCCN Cancer Screening; ESMO Guidelines', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
