select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: surgical pharmacology — chemotherapy + targeted therapy intro

คำถาม: principles of systemic cancer therapy', '[{"label":"A","text":"Chemotherapy alone for all cancers"},{"label":"B","text":"**Systemic cancer therapy — major classes + principles**: (1) **Cytotoxic chemotherapy** — DNA damage / mitosis disruption: - **Alkylating agents** (cisplatin, cyclophosphamide, ifosfamide, oxaliplatin, temozolomide): DNA cross-linking; SE: myelosuppression, nephro, neuropathy (oxali, cisplatin), nausea - **Antimetabolites** (5-FU, capecitabine, methotrexate, gemcitabine, pemetrexed): inhibit DNA synthesis; SE: mucositis, myelo, hand-foot - **Anti-tumor antibiotics** (doxorubicin, epirubicin, bleomycin): topoisomerase II inhibition; SE: cardiotoxicity (anthracyclines — cumulative dose dependent, baseline echo), pulmonary fibrosis (bleo) - **Mitotic inhibitors** (taxanes — paclitaxel, docetaxel, nab-paclitaxel; vinca alkaloids — vincristine, vinblastine): microtubule disruption; SE: peripheral neuropathy (taxanes, vinca), myelo, hypersensitivity (taxanes) - **Topoisomerase inhibitors** (irinotecan, etoposide): SE: diarrhea (irinotecan), myelo - **Platinums** see alkylating; (2) **Targeted therapy** — molecular alteration-directed: - **Tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKI)** — many; imatinib (BCR-ABL CML, GIST), erlotinib/gefitinib/osimertinib (EGFR NSCLC), sorafenib/sunitinib (multikinase — RCC, HCC, GIST), trastuzumab + tucatinib (HER2), BRAF inhibitors (dabrafenib, encorafenib + MEK inhibitor), ALK inhibitors (crizotinib, alectinib, lorlatinib), ROS1, RET (selpercatinib, pralsetinib), NTRK (larotrectinib, entrectinib), KRAS G12C (sotorasib, adagrasib), FLT3, IDH1/2, FGFR, MET ex14 (capmatinib, tepotinib), HER2 (ado-trastuzumab emtansine + others) - **Monoclonal antibodies**: rituximab (CD20, B-cell lymphoma), trastuzumab (HER2 breast/gastric), bevacizumab (VEGF), cetuximab + panitumumab (EGFR colorectal), pembrolizumab + nivolumab + atezolizumab + durvalumab + ipilimumab (immune checkpoint), daratumumab (CD38 myeloma), polatuzumab (CD79b) - **Antibody-drug conjugates (ADCs)**: trastuzumab emtansine (T-DM1), trastuzumab deruxtecan (T-DXd — HER2 + HER2-low), sacituzumab govitecan (TROP2), enfortumab vedotin (nectin-4 bladder), polatuzumab vedotin; (3) **Hormone therapy**: - Breast: SERM (tamoxifen, raloxifene), aromatase inhibitor (anastrozole, letrozole, exemestane), fulvestrant, GnRH agonist (premenopausal ovarian suppression — goserelin) - Prostate: GnRH agonist/antagonist (leuprolide, degarelix), anti-androgen (bicalutamide, enzalutamide, apalutamide, darolutamide), CYP17 inhibitor (abiraterone) - PARP inhibitors: olaparib, talazoparib, niraparib, rucaparib — BRCA+ + others; (4) **Immunotherapy**: - **Immune checkpoint inhibitors (ICIs)** — PD-1, PD-L1, CTLA-4: durable responses; IRAEs (immune-related adverse events) — colitis, hepatitis, pneumonitis, endocrine (thyroid, pituitary, adrenal), nephritis, dermatitis, myocarditis (rare but severe); manage with steroid + sometimes biologics (infliximab, mycophenolate) - **CAR-T (Chimeric Antigen Receptor T cell)**: tisagenlecleucel + others for B-cell ALL, lymphoma, multiple myeloma; SE: CRS (cytokine release syndrome — tocilizumab), ICANS (neurotoxicity) - **TILs (tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes)**: lifileucel — first FDA-approved for advanced melanoma (2024); (5) **Combination + sequencing**: - Curative regimens (Hodgkin ABVD, DLBCL R-CHOP, testicular BEP, neoadjuvant breast TCHP, etc.) - Adjuvant - Palliative; (6) **Personalized medicine** — molecular profiling guides therapy: tumor sequencing (NGS panels — Foundation, Tempus, MSK-IMPACT), liquid biopsy, biomarkers (MSI, TMB, HRD, PD-L1, HER2, ER/PR, EGFR, etc.); (7) **Toxicity management** — supportive care, antiemetics (5-HT3 + NK1 + steroid), GCSF, ESA selective, mucositis care, neuropathy, cardiac monitoring (echo for anthracyclines + HER2 agents), pneumonitis (steroid), endocrine (replacement), infusion reactions"},{"label":"C","text":"No specific knowledge needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Same drug for all cancers"},{"label":"E","text":"Avoid all systemic therapy"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Systemic cancer therapy** — multiple modalities; molecularly-targeted treatments transformed oncology. Major classes: 1. **Cytotoxic chemotherapy** — non-specific cell killing (preferentially fast-dividing cells); backbone for many; common SE: myelosuppression, mucositis, nausea, hair loss, neuropathy 2. **Targeted therapy** — molecularly directed: - TKIs (oral, manageable) - Monoclonal antibodies - ADCs (antibody-drug conjugates) - PARP inhibitors (BRCA, HRD) 3. **Hormone therapy** — breast (HR+), prostate (AR+) 4. **Immunotherapy** — ICIs (PD-1/PD-L1/CTLA-4), CAR-T, TILs, bispecifics 5. **Radiopharmaceuticals** — Lu-177-PSMA prostate (PSMAfore, VISION), Lu-177-DOTATATE NET (NETTER-1) 6. **Combinations + sequencing** based on disease + biology **Precision oncology principles**: - Tumor molecular profiling (NGS, IHC, FISH) - Biomarker-driven (MSI-H, TMB-high, HER2+, EGFR mutation, ALK fusion, BRAF V600E, KRAS G12C, etc.) - Tumor-agnostic approvals based on biomarker (pembrolizumab MSI-H, larotrectinib NTRK fusion, dabrafenib + trametinib BRAF V600E, dostarlimab dMMR rectal) - Liquid biopsy (ctDNA) for monitoring + resistance **Common toxicities + management**: - Nausea/vomiting: 5-HT3 (ondansetron) + NK1 (aprepitant) + dexamethasone + olanzapine emerging - Myelosuppression: GCSF (filgrastim, pegfilgrastim) for neutropenia prophylaxis in high-risk regimens - Mucositis: oral care, palifermin selected - Peripheral neuropathy (taxanes, vinca, oxaliplatin): often dose-limiting; duloxetine for symptoms; preventive trials largely negative - Cardiotoxicity (anthracyclines, HER2 agents, fluoropyrimidines): baseline + serial echo; dexrazoxane selected - Pneumonitis (bleomycin, mTOR inhibitor, ICIs): steroid, drug discontinuation - Hand-foot syndrome (capecitabine, sorafenib, sunitinib): topical care, dose adjust **Immune-related adverse events (IRAEs)** from ICIs: - Colitis: infliximab if steroid-refractory - Hepatitis: steroid; mycophenolate if refractory - Pneumonitis: steroid - Endocrine (thyroid most common, pituitary, adrenal, T1DM): replacement therapy - Dermatitis: topical + systemic steroid - Myocarditis: rare but severe; high-dose steroid + ATG/IVIG/mycophenolate; cardiology - Nephritis, hematologic, neurologic Multidisciplinary involvement essential for IRAE management. **CAR-T cell therapy** — autologous T-cells engineered to recognize tumor antigen (e.g., CD19 B-cell ALL, lymphoma; BCMA multiple myeloma). Toxicities: CRS (tocilizumab), ICANS (neurologic). Logistical complexity, cost, specialized centers.', NULL,
  'hard', 'hemato_onco', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'hemato_onco', 'adult',
  'NCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines; ASCO + ESMO; FDA approvals', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
