select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: pediatric trauma

คำถาม: pediatric trauma — key differences from adult', '[{"label":"A","text":"Same as adult"},{"label":"B","text":"**Pediatric trauma — distinct considerations**: (1) **Anatomic + physiologic differences**: - Larger head:body ratio → head injury common - Open fontanelles + sutures (infant) → expandable cranium initially → late deterioration possible - Higher % cartilage → less rib fractures but more underlying lung injury - More compliant chest wall → pulmonary contusion common without rib fracture - Smaller body mass + thinner abdominal wall → more multi-organ injury from single insult - Solid organs proportionally larger - Higher surface area:mass → faster heat loss → hypothermia risk - Higher BP, lower HR baselines; physiological vitals age-specific - Compensatory mechanisms maintain BP until ~ 30% blood loss → late decompensation - Spine immature — SCIWORA (Spinal Cord Injury Without Radiographic Abnormality) - Airway anatomy: larger tongue, more anterior + cephalad larynx (C3-4), funnel shape narrowest at cricoid until ~ 8 yr; (2) **Common mechanisms**: MVA (passenger + pedestrian), falls, drowning, burns, abuse, sports, recreational; (3) **Triage + transport**: pediatric trauma centers improve outcomes for severely injured; field triage criteria with pediatric considerations; (4) **Resuscitation**: - **Weight-based** dosing (Broselow tape, length-based) - **Vital sign norms** age-specific - **IV/IO access** — IO common + reliable in pediatric (proximal tibia, distal femur, proximal humerus) - **Fluid resuscitation**: 20 mL/kg crystalloid bolus × 2-3, then blood products (10-20 mL/kg PRC, FFP, platelets) - **Permissive hypotension** less established in pediatric than adult - **TXA**: pediatric dose 15 mg/kg (max 1 g) - **Damage control resuscitation** principles applied; (5) **Imaging**: minimize radiation (ALARA — as low as reasonably achievable); modified low-dose CT protocols + selective imaging; ultrasound (FAST) + MRI for spine + brain when feasible; (6) **Specific injuries — pediatric considerations**: - **Head injury**: CT for moderate-severe; PECARN rules for selective CT in minor head injury - **C-spine**: NEXUS pediatric, Canadian C-spine rule modifications; SCIWORA in young children - **Thoracic**: pulmonary contusion + flail rare due to compliant ribs; hemothorax + pneumothorax + cardiac/great vessel injury - **Abdominal**: solid organ injury (liver, spleen, kidney) — high NOM success in pediatric vs adult; conservative management threshold lower - **Pelvic**: less common (immature pelvis); when present often severe - **Long bone**: ossifying skeleton; growth plate injuries (Salter-Harris); minimize CT - **Burns**: larger surface area:mass → higher fluid requirement + heat loss; pediatric-specific burn formulas; Modified Brooke or Parkland with Lund-Browder chart; (7) **Non-accidental trauma (child abuse) consideration** — always assess: - Inconsistent history - Multiple stages of injuries - Specific patterns (bilateral, posterior rib fractures, metaphyseal corner fractures, retinal hemorrhages, abusive head trauma) - Mandatory reporting + child protective services involvement - Skeletal survey + careful documentation - Specialty consult (child abuse pediatricians); (8) **Pain control**: weight-based; multimodal; family-centered; (9) **Psychological + family-centered care**: PTSD + emotional impact; family presence during procedures + resuscitation (supported by evidence); Child Life specialists; (10) **Outcomes**: pediatric better than adult for similar severity due to physiologic reserve + healing; high NOM success solid organ; long-term follow-up for development, growth, scar contracture (burns)"},{"label":"C","text":"Surgery for all pediatric trauma"},{"label":"D","text":"No family involvement"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore abuse consideration"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Pediatric trauma** — distinct from adult; specialized knowledge + dedicated centers improve outcomes. **Key anatomic + physiologic differences**: 1. **Larger head:body ratio** — TBI most common cause of death in pediatric trauma 2. **Compliant chest wall** — pulmonary + cardiac injury common without rib fracture; rib fracture is a marker of high-energy mechanism (worry about underlying injury) 3. **Compensated shock** — children maintain BP until ~ 30-40% blood loss; tachycardia + delayed capillary refill + mental status changes are EARLIER signs; HYPOTENSION IS LATE FINDING — don''t be reassured by ''normal'' BP 4. **Higher surface area:mass** — rapid heat loss; aggressive warming + fluid warmers + ambient room temp; hypothermia worsens coagulopathy 5. **Airway anatomy** — larger tongue, anterior larynx, funnel shape (narrowest at cricoid until 8 yr); pediatric airway management differences 6. **SCIWORA** — Spinal Cord Injury Without Radiographic Abnormality — younger children; MRI for clinical suspicion despite normal X-ray/CT 7. **Open growth plates** — Salter-Harris classification I-V for physeal injuries; ortho involvement 8. **Vital signs age-specific** — pediatric norms (HR + RR higher, BP lower than adult; weight-based pressure norms) **Pediatric trauma triage** — to pediatric trauma centers when severely injured; verified pediatric trauma centers improve outcomes for major injuries (especially head, abdomen). **Resuscitation differences**: - Weight-based dosing (Broselow color-coded length tape) - IV access often difficult — IO (intraosseous) reliable + fast - Fluid: 20 mL/kg crystalloid boluses up to 60 mL/kg; then blood (10-20 mL/kg PRC) - TXA: 15 mg/kg (max 1 g) - DCR principles apply **PECARN rules** — pediatric head injury — selective CT vs observation in minor head trauma; reduces radiation exposure. **Imaging principles**: ALARA — minimize radiation, especially CT; US (FAST) + MRI when feasible; weighing diagnostic yield vs radiation. **Pediatric NOM (non-operative management)** — solid organ injury (spleen, liver, kidney) success > 90% in pediatric across grades (vs lower in adult); preserve organ when possible. **Non-accidental trauma (NAT) / Child abuse** — must consider in any pediatric trauma; specific patterns + history-injury mismatch raise suspicion; multidisciplinary including child abuse pediatricians + social work + mandatory reporting + protective services + skeletal survey + ophthalmology (abusive head trauma — retinal hemorrhages). **Burns in children**: - Lund-Browder more accurate than Rule of Nines (head proportionally larger in young) - Higher fluid requirement per body weight - Heat loss greater - Specific formulas (Parkland modified for pediatric: 3-4 mL/kg/%TBSA + maintenance with D5LR) - Family-centered burn care; abuse consideration. **Family-centered care + Child Life specialists** — psychological + emotional support; family presence during resuscitation supported by pediatric guidelines + ACS recommendations.', NULL,
  'medium', 'pediatrics', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'pediatrics', 'child',
