select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ระบบ EMS: telemedicine + remote consultation

คำถาม: telemedicine in surgical care', '[{"label":"A","text":"Not applicable"},{"label":"B","text":"**Telemedicine in surgery — emerging integrated care**: (1) **Synchronous** (real-time video) vs **asynchronous** (store-and-forward) consultation; (2) **Common applications**: - **Pre-operative consultation** — initial visit, history, education; physical exam + imaging review limited by modality - **Post-operative follow-up** — uncomplicated wound check, suture removal scheduling, recovery progress, medication adjustment; reduces travel burden + costs - **Surgical second opinions** — specialty consultation, complex case multidisciplinary review - **Inpatient consultation** — tele-trauma, tele-ICU, e-consults - **Remote monitoring** — wearables, home pulse-ox, smart bandages, post-op symptoms checklists - **Tele-mentoring + tele-proctoring** — experienced surgeon guides remote surgeon; useful global health + rural - **Telesurgery** (true remote operation) — proof-of-concept (Lindbergh 2001 NY to Strasbourg); 5G enabling; growing in selected countries (China, others); not mainstream yet; (3) **Benefits**: - Access (rural, mobility-limited, time-constrained patients) - Cost-effectiveness - Time-efficient for selected encounters - Multi-site coordination - Mental health + psychological support integration - Reduced infection exposure (post-COVID acceleration); (4) **Limitations**: - Physical exam limited - Procedure planning may need in-person - Imaging review limited by display + connectivity - Digital divide / equity concerns - Privacy + security - Reimbursement evolving - Licensure across jurisdictions; (5) **Quality + safety considerations**: - Patient selection (appropriateness for telemedicine) - Documentation standards - Workflow integration - Backup for technology failure - Standards (American Telemedicine Association, ACS Telehealth Steering Committee); (6) **Tele-trauma + tele-ICU**: - Remote trauma consultation for rural hospitals — improves outcomes (Latifi et al studies) - Tele-ICU model (eICU) — real-time monitoring + intervention; mortality benefit in some implementations; (7) **Specific surgical specialty uses**: - Dermatology (skin lesion images, asynchronous) - Wound care - Bariatric pre/post-op surveillance - Oncology survivorship - Pediatric surgical screening - ENT (endoscopic video review); (8) **Implementation considerations**: - Equity — broadband access, device access, digital literacy, language - Quality assurance + outcome tracking - Workflow + EHR integration - Reimbursement + regulation (CMS, state) - Cross-jurisdiction licensure (state lines US — increasingly harmonized) - Cybersecurity + HIPAA - Cultural + linguistic sensitivity; (9) **COVID-19 catalyzed** rapid telemedicine expansion; many policies relaxed temporarily; some sustained; sustainability + appropriateness ongoing; (10) **Future**: continued integration; AI integration (triage, image analysis); hybrid in-person + virtual care; cross-border health systems; global tele-surgical mentorship"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid technology"},{"label":"D","text":"Replace all in-person care"},{"label":"E","text":"Single application only"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Telemedicine in surgical care** — increasingly integrated; accelerated by COVID-19 pandemic. **Applications across surgical care continuum**: 1. **Pre-operative**: initial consultation, history, education, multidisciplinary case review 2. **Operative**: tele-proctoring + tele-mentoring (experienced surgeon supervises remote surgeon — used in fellowship training + rural / LMIC support) 3. **Post-operative**: routine follow-up for uncomplicated procedures; remote monitoring 4. **Specialty consultations**: tele-trauma, tele-ICU, e-consults (asynchronous) **Telesurgery** (true remote operation via robotic systems): - Lindbergh Operation 2001 (Marescaux, NY to Strasbourg) — proof-of-concept cholecystectomy - Modern: 5G enabling lower latency; growing in selected (China + others) - Not mainstream in most healthcare systems yet - Issues: latency, safety, redundancy, regulatory **Tele-ICU (eICU)**: centralized off-site critical care team monitors + intervenes in remote ICUs; some studies show mortality benefit + improved metrics (Lilly + others); cost-effectiveness debated; staffing model varies. **Tele-trauma**: rural ED consultation with trauma surgeon at level I center; improves decision-making + reduces unnecessary transfers; Latifi et al + others evidence. **Benefits**: - Access — rural, mobility-limited, isolated - Cost + time efficiency - Specialist availability - Pandemic response (reduced exposure) **Limitations + challenges**: - Physical exam limitations - Quality of video / connection - Digital divide (broadband, device, literacy) - Privacy + cybersecurity - Reimbursement (variable + evolving) - Cross-state licensure (US — Interstate Medical Licensure Compact helps; full reciprocity not yet) - International licensure - Quality assurance + outcome tracking **Equity considerations**: digital divide may worsen disparities for rural, low-income, elderly, non-English speaking populations; mitigation: community broadband, device lending, translators, hybrid care, kiosks, mobile clinics. **AI integration**: triage chatbots, image analysis (dermatology, radiology), risk prediction, documentation NLP. **Regulatory**: FDA for medical devices (including remote surgery), state medical boards, CMS reimbursement, HIPAA + privacy, malpractice insurance considerations. **Standards**: American Telemedicine Association (ATA), ACS Telehealth Steering Committee, specialty society guidelines.', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'ems_mgmt', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'American Telemedicine Association; ACS Telehealth; Latifi R et al. World J Surg', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_ems_mgmt'
