select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'หญิงไทยอายุ 45 ปี post-open cholecystectomy 5 วันก่อน มา ED ด้วยอาการ jaundice + ปวด RUQ + ไข้ + อาเจียน

VS: BP 102/64, HR 116, Temp 38.6, jaundice prominent
Lab: Total bili 8.4, Direct 7.2, ALP 480, AST 220, ALT 168, WBC 17,200, CRP 220
MRCP: complete transection CBD at hepatic hilum + biloma + dilated intrahepatic ducts (Strasberg E2 / Bismuth III injury)', '[{"label":"A","text":"Observation alone"},{"label":"B","text":"**Major iatrogenic bile duct injury (Strasberg E2 / Bismuth III) — emergent + definitive management**: (1) **Initial**: IV broad-spectrum antibiotic (covering biliary flora — pip-tazo OR ceftriaxone + metronidazole), resuscitation, sepsis management; (2) **Source control**: - **Percutaneous transhepatic biliary drainage (PTBD)** of dilated intrahepatic ducts — relieves obstruction + treats cholangitis; bilateral if needed - **Drainage of biloma** percutaneously (IR) - **NPO + nutritional support**; (3) **Definitive reconstruction — referral to high-volume HPB center** (better outcomes per literature): - **Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy** — gold standard for major proximal bile duct injuries - Timing: ideally delayed 6-8 weeks for inflammation to subside + adequate drainage; immediate only in unstable / unable to drain - Identify proximal healthy duct + bring up Roux limb 60 cm + mucosa-to-mucosa anastomosis; (4) **End-to-end repair** — only feasible for short segment defects with minimal tissue loss + no inflammation; high stricture rate; avoid in major proximal injuries; (5) **Strasberg-Bismuth classification**: - A: cystic duct stump leak - B: aberrant right duct ligated - C: aberrant right duct leak (open) - D: lateral CBD injury - E1-E5: hilar/bifurcation involvement (E1 distal, E5 right hepatic sectoral involvement separate from main hilum) - Higher level = more complex repair; (6) **Outcomes**: best at high-volume HPB centers; stricture + recurrent cholangitis remain common long-term; 5-yr patency after HJ ~ 75-90% in expert centers; (7) **Long-term**: surveillance for stricture (LFT, MRCP), portal HTN/biliary cirrhosis if chronic obstruction, recurrent cholangitis; (8) **Legal + disclosure**: open communication with patient + family per principles of open disclosure"},{"label":"C","text":"Liver transplant only"},{"label":"D","text":"Continue conservative"},{"label":"E","text":"Whipple procedure"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Major iatrogenic bile duct injury** — devastating complication of cholecystectomy (laparoscopic 0.3-0.6%, open 0.1-0.2%). **Strasberg-Bismuth Classification**: - **A**: cystic duct/duct of Luschka leak — ERCP + stent + drain - **B**: aberrant right hepatic duct ligation — atrophy, may not need intervention - **C**: aberrant right hepatic duct leak — drain + reconstruction - **D**: lateral CBD injury — primary repair over T-tube if early + clean - **E1**: CBD > 2 cm from confluence - **E2**: CBD < 2 cm from confluence - **E3**: at confluence (right + left hepatic intact) - **E4**: at confluence with destruction (right + left separate) - **E5**: aberrant right sectoral + main CBD **Recognition**: - Intra-op (~ 30%) — best outcomes if recognized + repaired by HPB surgeon - Early post-op (days-weeks) — bile leak, biloma, peritonitis, cholangitis, jaundice - Late (months-years) — stricture, recurrent cholangitis, biliary cirrhosis **Management principles**: 1. **Multidisciplinary** — refer to high-volume HPB center; outcomes substantially better than general surgery center 2. **Source control first** — biliary decompression (PTBD or ERCP-stent if amenable), drain biliary collections (biloma), antibiotic for cholangitis 3. **Definitive reconstruction**: - **Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy** — gold standard for E1-E5; - End-to-end repair only for short clean defects (rare with major injuries); - Timing: typically delayed 6-8 weeks for inflammation to resolve + adequate drainage of biliary tree + nutritional optimization; immediate only in extenuating circumstances 4. **Surgical technique**: identify healthy proximal duct, transect at level of viable mucosa, 60 cm Roux limb (no reflux), mucosa-to-mucosa anastomosis with absorbable suture, transanastomotic stent (controversial — not universal), preserve duct blood supply **Outcomes** at high-volume HPB centers: - Primary patency 80-90% at 5 years - Secondary intervention (balloon dilation, restenting) for late strictures - Recurrent cholangitis 10-20% - Quality of life significantly improved with appropriate management vs untreated **Strasberg + Critical View of Safety** — best practice for cholecystectomy to prevent BDI: clear identification of cystic duct + cystic artery, only 2 structures entering gallbladder, before clipping or transection.', NULL,
  'hard', 'gi', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'gi', 'adult',
  'Strasberg SM et al. J Am Coll Surg; SAGES Safe Cholecystectomy Program; Jablonska B + Lampe P World J Gastroenterol', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
      and q.board_specialty = 'surgery'
      and q.scenario = 'หญิงไทยอายุ 45 ปี post-open cholecystectomy 5 วันก่อน มา ED ด้วยอาการ jaundice + ปวด RUQ + ไข้ + อาเจียน

VS: BP 102/64, HR 116, Temp 38.6, jaundice prominent
Lab: Total bili 8.4, Direct 7.2, ALP 480, AST 220, ALT 168, WBC 17,200, CRP 220
MRCP: complete transection CBD at hepatic hilum + biloma + dilated intrahepatic ducts (Strasberg E2 / Bismuth III injury)'
  );

