select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: surgical pathology + frozen section

คำถาม: intraoperative frozen section + pathology', '[{"label":"A","text":"Not relevant to surgery"},{"label":"B","text":"**Intraoperative pathology + frozen section — surgical decision-making tool**: (1) **Frozen section**: - Rapid tissue examination (~ 20-30 min) during operation - Cryostat freezing + H&E stain - Pathologist reads + reports immediately - Guides surgical decision in real-time; (2) **Common indications**: - **Confirm malignancy** before extensive resection - **Assess margin status** (e.g., breast lumpectomy, Mohs, brain tumor, soft tissue sarcoma) - **Identify sentinel lymph node positivity** — though less common now (postpone definitive axillary decision often) - **Identify tissue origin** (parathyroid vs lymph node vs thyroid during neck exploration) - **Assess for invasion** (DCIS vs invasive, follicular lesion of thyroid) - **Identify foreign body or unexpected findings**; (3) **Limitations of frozen section**: - Less detail than permanent (formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded — FFPE) - Limited tissue sampling (small piece may miss disease) - Some tissue types difficult on frozen (lipoma vs liposarcoma, follicular thyroid lesion — cannot distinguish benign follicular adenoma from carcinoma on frozen; requires capsular/vascular invasion assessment best on permanent) - Freezing artifact - Some immunohistochemistry not available on frozen - Higher discordance with permanent in difficult cases (~ 1-3%); (4) **Specific applications**: a. **Breast surgery**: - Margin assessment (frozen + ''shave'' margins) - SLN biopsy (some centers — less common now post Z0011) - Touch prep / imprint cytology adjunct b. **Thyroid surgery**: - Confirm malignancy if not pre-confirmed (uncommon — usually FNA Bethesda guides) - LN involvement c. **Mohs micrographic surgery**: - Skin cancer (BCC, SCC, melanoma in situ selected) - Real-time margin assessment + sequential excision until clear d. **Lung surgery**: - Wedge biopsy → frozen → decide lobectomy vs further if cancer e. **Brain surgery**: - Tumor identification + grading f. **Sarcoma**: - Margin assessment - Tumor identification g. **Lymph node**: - Lymphoma vs metastatic carcinoma h. **Parathyroid surgery**: - Confirm parathyroid tissue (vs lymph node, thyroid, fat) - Intraoperative PTH adjunct; (5) **Permanent / final pathology** — gold standard: - Formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE) - More accurate, comprehensive evaluation - Standard H&E + immunohistochemistry + special stains - Molecular testing (NGS, FISH, IHC for predictive markers) - Reported within days-weeks - Used for: comprehensive diagnosis, prognosis, biomarkers, treatment decisions; (6) **Communication with pathologist** essential: - Provide clinical context - Specific question to answer - Collaborative decision-making - Multidisciplinary tumor board for complex; (7) **Tissue handling principles**: - Proper labeling + orientation (sutures, ink) - Avoid crush + thermal injury - Send fresh for frozen if needed; otherwise formalin - Special handling: lymphoma flow cytometry (fresh tissue), microbiologic, electron microscopy; (8) **Molecular pathology + companion diagnostics** — increasing role: - Tumor genotyping guides targeted therapy - Liquid biopsy emerging - Predictive biomarkers (ER/PR/HER2 breast, EGFR/ALK/PD-L1 lung, MSI/dMMR, BRCA, etc.)"},{"label":"C","text":"No pathology needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Single test for all"},{"label":"E","text":"Frozen section replaces permanent"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Intraoperative pathology + frozen section** — important surgical decision-making tool. **Frozen section process**: - Surgeon submits tissue (fresh, properly oriented) - Cryostat freezing (~ 5 min) - Sectioning + H&E staining - Microscopic interpretation by pathologist - Verbal report to surgeon (typically 15-30 min total) - Decision made intraoperatively **Common surgical applications**: 1. **Margin assessment** — breast (lumpectomy, post-mastectomy), brain tumors, sarcoma, head/neck, GU (prostatectomy) 2. **Diagnosis confirmation** before extensive surgery (e.g., presumed primary lung Ca on biopsy → wedge resection → frozen confirms → lobectomy + lymphadenectomy) 3. **Sentinel lymph node** — historically; declining role post-ACOSOG Z0011 (axillary dissection not always needed for 1-2 positive SLN in breast Ca with BCS + RT) 4. **Tissue identification** — parathyroidectomy (confirm parathyroid vs LN/thyroid/fat) 5. **Mohs surgery** — skin cancer real-time margin assessment **Limitations**: - Less detail than permanent (frozen vs FFPE) - Sampling limitations - Difficult tissues: lipoma vs liposarcoma, follicular thyroid neoplasm (cannot reliably distinguish benign vs malignant on frozen — requires capsular/vascular invasion assessment best on permanent) - Freezing artifact - Limited IHC + molecular - Discordance with permanent ~ 1-3% (false-positive + false-negative both occur) **Communication with pathologist** key: - Clinical context + specific question - Multidisciplinary input on difficult cases - Defer to permanent if uncertain on frozen (often appropriate) **Tissue handling**: - Orientation (ink colors, sutures for margins) - Avoid crush + thermal damage - Fresh for frozen + microbiology + flow cytometry (lymphoma); formalin for permanent - Special: electron microscopy, molecular **Molecular pathology + companion diagnostics** — increasing role in surgical pathology: - **NGS** (next-generation sequencing) panels — tumor genotyping - **IHC** for predictive markers (ER/PR/HER2 breast; PD-L1 lung; HER2 gastric; ER+ endometrial; etc.) - **FISH** (HER2 amplification, ALK rearrangement, others) - **Liquid biopsy** (ctDNA, CTCs) — minimal residual disease, recurrence monitoring, resistance mutations - **MSI / dMMR** — colorectal + others; immunotherapy candidacy + Lynch screening - **HRD** (homologous recombination deficiency) — PARP inhibitor predictive (ovarian, breast, prostate) **Reporting standards**: synoptic reporting (CAP — College of American Pathologists protocols) ensures all critical information captured + standardized; improves communication + decision-making.', NULL,
  'easy', 'hemato_onco', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'hemato_onco', 'adult',
  'CAP (College of American Pathologists) Protocols; WHO Tumor Classification; ASCO/CAP Guidelines', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
